º How it works? ³
ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¾

    Program needs MS-DOS 3.3 or higher and about 150K free RAM to run.


    Just run the Q-Setup!

    The only one parameter available - is CONVERT <file> .  This  will help
you to make  your own character redefinition table and easily convert it to
the QVIEW.CHR then.
    To define table you should  start with the NAME keyword followed by the
table name. All after the #0, #9  and ';' characters are ignored.  From the
next strings you may start to  define character. Note, that by default each
caracter is redefined to itself so you may redefine the only characters you
need.
    You may define character  by  its number as well as by literal. Numbers
are  always decimal;  literal  characters are enclosed in single quotes;  a
semicolon separate definition at  the same  line;  blank spaces,  tabs  and
carriage returns are ignored. E.g.:
                                'û'='ş'; 246='õ'
                               245=244; 'ê' = 39
    You may use up to 255-bytes per line.
    The first character is what you are want to translate,  the second - to
what character it should be tranlated.


    Think I should not give you more notices - just refer the help on F1.


    Program operates with three files - QVIEW.INI, QVIEW.FMG and QVIEW.EHL.
These files should be placed in the sturt-up directory of Q-Setup. If they
are not,  the built-in settings will be used.  And  these  files  will  be
created when you hit F2 (Save).

    The start-up directory may not be the current one. It's ok, if you type
the path to the setup in the command line or if the start-up directory will
be specified in the %PATH% variable.

